2)What is Nullable Types in C#?
->Nullable types in C# allow value types (like int, bool, DateTime) to store null values.
They are useful when a variable may not have a value.

Short Syntax (?)
int? age = null;
bool? isActive = true;

Long Syntax
Nullable<int> marks = null;


3)What is String Operations in C#?
->String operations in C# are methods and techniques used to manipulate strings, such as creating, modifying, comparing, searching, and formatting text data.
  string first = "Hello";
  string second = "World";
  string result = first + " " + second;

  string name = "Rahul";
  Console.WriteLine(name.Length);   // 5

  string text = "CSharp";
  string part = text.Substring(1, 3);  // Sha

  string msg = "Hello World";
  string newMsg = msg.Replace("World", "C#");

  string name = "Manan";
  Console.WriteLine(name.ToUpper());
  Console.WriteLine(name.ToLower());

  string data = "  Hello  ";
  Console.WriteLine(data.Trim());

  string email = "test@gmail.com";

  email.Contains("@");
  email.StartsWith("test");
  email.EndsWith(".com");

  string line = "A,B,C";
  string[] values = line.Split(',');

  string a = "Hello";
  string b = "hello";
  bool equal = a.Equals(b, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);

  string name = "Rahul";
  int age = 25
  Console.WriteLine($"Name: {name}, Age: {age}");


4)What is StringBuilder?
->StringBuilder is a class in C# used to create and modify strings efficiently without creating new string objects every time.
It is useful when string data changes frequently.

using System.Text;
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
sb.Append("Hello");
sb.Append(" ");
sb.Append("World");
Console.WriteLine(sb.ToString());
->Common StringBuilder Methods
Append()
AppendLine()
Insert()
Remove()
Replace()
Clear()

5)Constant (const) vs ReadOnly (readonly) in C#?
->const (Constant)
  A constant is a variable whose value is fixed at compile time and cannot be changed ever.
->readonly
  A readonly variable is a field whose value can be assigned only once, either at declaration time or inside a constructor, and cannot be modified afterward.

6)What is C# Properties: Auto, Backed & Expression-Bodied?
->Property (General)
  A property in C# is a member that provides controlled access to a class field using get and set accessors.
->Auto-Implemented Property
  An auto property is a property where the compiler automatically creates the backing field.
  It is used when no extra logic is needed in get/set.

->Backed Property
  A backed property (backing-field property) uses a private field to store the value and allows custom logic in get/set.

->Expression-Bodied Property
  An expression-bodied property is a short, concise syntax for properties that return a single expression.

1ï¸âƒ£ Auto-Implemented Property
   Example
   class Student
   {
    public int Age { get; set; }
    }
2ï¸âƒ£ Backed Property (Private Field)
    Example
    class Student
    {
    private int _age;
    public int Age
    {
        get { return _age; }
        set
        {
            if (value > 0)
                _age = value;
        }
     }
    }
3ï¸âƒ£ Expression-Bodied Property
class Student
{
    public string FirstName { get; set; }
    public string LastName { get; set; }

    public string FullName => $"{FirstName} {LastName}";
}

7)Stack vs Heap Memory (C#)?
| Feature      |  Stack Memory| Heap Memory            |
| ------------ | ------------ | ---------------------- |
| Storage      | Value types  | Reference types        |
| Allocation   | Automatic    | Dynamic                |
| Deallocation | Automatic    | Garbage Collector      |
| Speed        | Fast         | Slower                 |
| Size         | Limited      | Large                  |
| Lifetime     | Method scope | Application controlled |
| Access       | Direct       | Reference-based        |


8)Boxing & Unboxing in C#?
->Boxing is the process of converting a value type into a reference type (object).
The value is wrapped inside an object and stored on the heap.

-Unboxing is the process of extracting the value type from the object back into its original value type.

9)Exception Handling in C# (try, catch, finally, throw)?
->Exception handling in C# is a mechanism used to handle runtime errors gracefully so that the program does not crash and continues execution in a controlled manner.
1ï¸âƒ£ try Block-> The try block contains code that may cause an exception during program execution.
2ï¸âƒ£ catch Block->The catch block handles the exception thrown in the try block and allows the program to continue execution.
3ï¸âƒ£ finally Block->The finally block contains code that is always executed, whether an exception occurs or not.
4ï¸âƒ£ throw Keyword->The throw keyword is used to explicitly generate an exception in a program.

10)Enum & Struct in C#?
->An enum is a value type that is used to define a set of named constant values, which makes the code more readable and meaningful.
Struct->A struct is a value type in C# used to group related variables of different data types into a single unit.

Enum (Enumeration)
enum Day
{
    Monday,
    Tuesday,
    Wednesday,
    Thursday,
    Friday
}
how to use
Day today = Day.Monday;
Struct
struct Employee
{
    public int Id;
    public string Name;
}
how to use
Employee emp;
emp.Id = 1;
emp.Name = "Rahul";

One-Line Summary
Enum â†’ Fixed named constants
Struct â†’ Small grouped data


-----------------------------------------------Object-Oriented Programming(oop)------------------------------------------------
1)What Is The Oops and difference Between Functional & Object Oritend Programming Langauge?
->OOPs is a programming style where a program is built using objects that contain data and functions.
->Object-oriented programming is a programming style where programs are created using classes and objects.
OOPs 4 Pillars
Encapsulation
Abstraction
Inheritance
Polymorphism
Functional programming is a programming style where programs are written using functions and data does not change.
| Feature             | Functional Programming | Object-Oriented Programming |
| ------------------- | ---------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Focus               | Functions              | Objects                     |
| Data                | Immutable              | Mutable                     |
| State               | Avoids state           | Uses state                  |
| Code style          | Declarative            | Imperative                  |
| Reusability         | Function reuse         | Class & inheritance         |
| Real-world modeling | Difficult              | Easy                        |
| Examples            | F#, Haskell            | C#, Java                    |

2)What Is Class & Objects?
->class->A class is a blueprint or template that defines the properties (data/fields) and methods (behavior/functions) for objects.
  It does not occupy memory until an object is created.
  Think of it as a design or plan for an entity.

->object->An object is a real-world instance of a class.
  It contains actual data in memory.
  Objects have state (properties) and behavior (methods) as defined in their class.

3)What Is Constructor & Destructors?
->A constructor is a special method in a class that is automatically called when an object is created.
->It is used to initialize objects and set default values.
->Constructor name must be the same as the class name.
->No return type, not even void.
Types Of Constructor
Default Constructor->Called automatically when no constructor is defined.
Parameterized Constructor->Allows passing values during object creation.
Static Constructor->Used to initialize static members of the class. Called once automatically when the class is loaded.
                    Cannot take parameters.
Copy Constructor->A Copy Constructor is a constructor that creates a new object by copying the data of an existing object of the same class.
C# does not provide a built-in copy constructor, but you can create your own.'

this Keyword in C#->The this keyword in C# refers to the current instance of the class.

Destuctors
A destructor is a special method in C# that is used to release resources and clean up memory when an object is destroyed.

4)What is Encapsulation?
->Encapsulation is the process of hiding data inside a class and only allowing it to be accessed through public methods or properties.
It is also known as data hiding.
Purpose / Why we use Encapsulation
To protect data from unauthorized access.
To make the code secure and maintainable.
To control how data is accessed or modified.
To implement data hiding using access modifiers (private, public, etc.).

5)What is Inheritance?
->inheritance is an OOP concept in which one class (child/derived) can reuse and extend the properties and methods of another class (parent/base).
It promotes:
Code reusability
Extensibility
Polymorphism

->Types Of Inheritance
Single Inheritance->One derived class inherits from one base class is called single Inheritance.
Multilevel Inheritance->A class inherits from another derived class (like a chain) is called Multilevel Inheritance.
Hierarchical Inheritance->Multiple classes inherit from the same base class is called Hierarchical Inheritance.
Multiple Inheritance (via Interface)
In C#, a class cannot inherit from more than one class directly (to avoid ambiguity).
But it can implement multiple interfaces.
Hybrid Inheritance (via Interface)->combination of more than one type of inheritance (like hierarchical + multiple).
In C#, hybrid inheritance is possible only using interfaces, not classes.


6)What is Ploymorphism(Compile-time & RunTime)?
->Polymorphism means â€œmany formsâ€ â€” it allows a single function, method, or object to behave differently in different situations.
It helps you reuse the same method name with different implementations
In simple words:
One name â€” many behaviors.
Types of Polymorphism in C#
1)Compile-time Polymorphism(Static Polymorphism)
2)Runtime Polymorphism (Dynamic Polymorphism)

Static Polymorphism (Compile-time Polymorphism)
->When a method performs different tasks based on parameters (number or type), it is called Static Polymorphism or Method Overloading.
It is resolved during compile time.
Same method name, different parameters.

->Runtime Polymorphism (also called Dynamic Polymorphism) occurs when a method in a base class is overridden in a derived class, and the method call is determined at runtime based on the object type.
In simple words:
The same method name behaves differently depending on the object that calls it.
Runtime polymorphism is achieved through:
Method Overriding
Using the virtual and override keywords
virtual keyword â†’ Allows the base class method to be overridden.
override keyword â†’ Defines a new implementation in the derived class.
Base class reference (Animal a) points to derived class objects (Dog, Cat).
At runtime, CLR (Common Language Runtime) decides which Speak() to call.

7)What is Abstract Classes & Methods?
->data abstraction
â€œAbstraction is the process of hiding the complex implementation details and showing only what is necessary.â€
In C#, it is achieved using abstract classes and interfaces.â€
Purpose of Abstraction
âœ… To reduce complexity of code
âœ… To improve security by hiding details
âœ… To focus on what an object does, not how it does it
âœ… Makes programs easier to understand and maintain

interface
An interface is a blueprint or contract that defines a set of methods and properties that a class must implement.
It helps achieve abstraction and multiple inheritance in C#.
| Feature              | Abstract Class                             | Interface                                 |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------- |
| **Contains**         | Abstract + Concrete methods                | Only abstract members                     |
| **Access Modifiers** | Can use `public`, `private`, etc.          | All members are public                    |
| **Inheritance**      | Supports single inheritance                | Supports multiple inheritance             |
| **Usage**            | Used for shared base with default behavior | Used for defining common behavior (rules) |


8)What is Sealed Classes?
->A sealed class in C# is a class that cannot be inherited by any other class is called to Sealed Class.
  Used for
Security, performance, fixed behavior.

9)What is Static Classes and Members?
->A static class is a class that cannot be instantiated and contains only static members.
->A static member (variable, method, property) belongs to the class itself, not to any object.

10)What is Partital Classes?
->A partial class allows a single class to be split into multiple files, but all parts are combined into one class at compile time.

11)What is Object Initializers?
->An object initializer allows you to create and initialize an object in a single statement without calling a constructor explicitly.

12)What is Access Modifier?
->>Access modifiers in C# are keywords that define the visibility or accessibility of classes, methods, and members.
They control which parts of a program can access a class or member.
Help in data encapsulation and security.
public->Member is accessible from anywhere 
        Everywhere in the project or assembly.
private->Member is accessible only within the class.
         Inside the class only
protected->Member is accessible within the class and derived classes.
           Class + inheritance.
internal->Member is accessible only within the same assembly.
         Same project/assembly.
protected internal->Member is accessible within the same assembly or derived class.
                  ->Combination of protected & internal.

13)what is Delegates & Events?
->Delegates->Type of Delegate:-
1) Single Cast Delegate:-We can call one delegate to one function
2) Multicast Delegate:- We can \point one delegate to multiple functions address

->Events->An event is a mechanism that allows a class to notify other classes when something happens, using delegates.

14)What is Lambda Expressions?
->A lambda expression is a short, anonymous function that is used to write inline logic without creating a separate method.
Example Without Lambda
int Add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}
Same Example Using Lambda
Func<int, int, int> add = (a, b) => a + b;
Console.WriteLine(add(2, 3));

15)What is Anonymous Methods?
->An anonymous method is a method without a name that is defined inline and assigned to a delegate.
ðŸ”¹ Example Without Anonymous Method
delegate void MyDelegate(int x);

static void Show(int x)
{
    Console.WriteLine(x);
}
MyDelegate d = Show;

ðŸ”¹ Same Example Using Anonymous Method
delegate void MyDelegate(int x);
MyDelegate d = delegate (int x)
{
    Console.WriteLine(x);
};
d(10);

16)what is Func,Action,Predicate?
->Func
Func is a generic delegate that takes parameters and returns a value.
->Action
Action is a generic delegate that takes parameters but does NOT return any value.
->Predicate
Predicate is a generic delegate that takes one parameter and always returns a boolean (true/false).

--------------------------------------------------------Collections & Generics --------------------------------------------------------------
1)What is The Array(1D,2D,Jagged)
->An array is a collection of same-type elements stored in continuous memory locations and accessed using an index.
1D Array->A 1D array is an array that stores elements in a single linear sequence and is accessed using one index.
2D Array->A 2D array is an array that stores data in rows and columns and is accessed using two indexes.
Jagged Array->A jagged array is an array of arrays where each inner array can have a different size.
| Feature   | 1D Array   | 2D Array           | Jagged Array         |
| --------- | ---------- | ------------------ | -------------------- |
| Structure | Linear     | Table              | Array of arrays      |
| Size      | Fixed      | Fixed rows/columns | Flexible             |
| Memory    | Continuous | Continuous         | Non-continuous       |
| Use Case  | List       | Matrix             | Variable-length rows |


2)What Is The NonGenric Collections?
->â€œCollections are containers that store multiple objects and provide methods to add, remove, or access elements easily.â€
 Non-Generic Collections (Namespace: System.Collections)->Can store any type of object.
->ArrayList->An ArrayList is a collection that stores elements of any type and manages the index automatically.
Methods: Add(), Remove(), Insert(), Contains().

->Hashtable->A Hashtable stores data in key-value pairs. Each value is accessed using a unique key.
Key must be unique.
Methods: Add(key, value), Remove(key), ContainsKey(key)

->SortedList
SortedList stores key-value pairs like Hashtable but automatically sorts elements in ascending order by key.
Combines features of Array List + Hash table
Can be generic or non-generic
Methods: Add(), Remove(), ContainsKey()

->>>Stack
A Stack stores elements in LIFO (Last In First Out) order.
The last item added is the first item retrieved.
Methods: Push() (add), Pop() (remove and return), Peek() (view top)
Both generic and non-generic stacks available.

->Queue
->A Queue stores elements in FIFO (First In First Out) order.
The first item added is the first item retrieved.
Methods: Enqueue() (add), Dequeue() (remove), Peek() (view first)
Both generic and non-generic queues available

3)What is Generic Collection?
->Generic Collections in C# are collections that store elements of a specific data type, providing type safety, better performance, and code optimization.
Types Generic Collections
List<T>->List<T> is a strongly typed dynamic array that stores elements of a specific type and automatically increases its size as elements are added.
Methods: Add(), Remove(), Sort(), Contains(), Count

Dictionary<TKey, TValue>->A Dictionary<TKey, TValue> stores data as key-value pairs.
Each key must be unique, and you can retrieve values using the key.
Methods: Add(), Remove(), ContainsKey(), TryGetValue()

HashSet<T>->A HashSet<T> stores unique elements and automatically removes duplicates.
No duplicates allowed
Unordered collection
Methods: Add(), Remove(), Contains()

Stack<T>->A Stack stores elements in LIFO (Last In First Out) order.
The last item added is the first item retrieved.
Methods: Push() (add), Pop() (remove and return), Peek() (view top)

Queue<T>
->A Queue stores elements in FIFO (First In First Out) order.
The first item added is the first item retrieved.
Methods: Enqueue() (add), Dequeue() (remove), Peek() (view first)


4)IEnumerable Vs IEnumerator
->IEnumerable
  IEnumerable is an interface that provides a collection for iteration and returns an IEnumerator.

->IEnumerator
 IEnumerator is an interface that controls the iteration process over a collection.

IEnumerable<int> numbers = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3 };
IEnumerator<int> enumerator = numbers.GetEnumerator();
while (enumerator.MoveNext())
{
    Console.WriteLine(enumerator.Current);
}

5)Yield return?
->yield return is used to return elements one at a time from a method, without creating a full collection, while maintaining the methodâ€™s state.
| return                 | yield return           |
| ---------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Returns once           | Returns multiple times |
| Method ends            | Method pauses          |
| Full collection needed | No collection needed   |


IEnumerable<int> EvenNumbers(int max)
 {
       for (int i = 2; i <= max; i += 2)
        {
               yield return i;
         }
 }
 foreach (int num in EvenNumbers(10))
 {
       Console.WriteLine(num);
 }




